&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]STFC W[bold]i[bold]STEM NETWORK [bold](WSC090) [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In contrast to other disciplines, STEM is per
[normal]ceived as 
[normal]a 
[normal]route to demonstrating personal achievement, rather than as an endeavour which improves peoples’ lives as a whole.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Within 
[normal]some 
[normal]STEM
[normal] fields (for example, chemistry, computational science, theoretical physics, etc.)
[normal], i
[normal]ndependent
[normal] work 
[normal]tends to be 
[normal]valued more than collaborative work
[normal] which in turn tends to favour male 
[normal]success factors
[normal]. For example, 
[normal]U
[normal]niversities require
[normal] senior staff to establish and lead their own 
[normal]independent 
[normal]research 
[normal]group
[normal]s; individually
[normal]-authored publications 
[normal]are a major m
[normal]easure of ability
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]STEM careers 
[normal]are often 
[normal]portrayed 
[normal]to be both 
[normal]all-consuming
[normal] 
[normal]and overwhelmingly competitive. There is a strong preconception that 
[normal]one cannot 
[normal]participate in science on anything other than a completely immersive basis.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]STEM careers
[normal] 
[normal]characteristically 
[normal]progress 
[normal]according 
[normal]to 
[normal]the 
[normal]prestige
[normal] built amongst peers, which is perceived to 
[normal]be in contrast to 
[normal]preferred measures of success
[normal] favoured by women
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]STEM career progression focusses on q
[normal]uantity 
[normal]as the 
[normal]most important measure of productivity (e.g. number of publications, 
[normal]citations, 
[normal]H-
[normal]index
[normal])
[normal] which militates against career breaks or reduced working hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Evaluation of 
[normal]success 
[normal]in STEM jobs 
[normal]typically 
[normal]relies heavily on 
[normal]‘quantity’ (see above), 
[normal]technical 
[normal]ability and intellectual rigor
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]but 
[normal]often 
[normal]fails to 
[normal]formally 
[normal]highlight 
[normal]and recognise 
[normal]facets of ability which have a significant impact on actual performance
[normal]. 
[normal]For example, a
[normal]cademic scientists spend a considerable 
[normal]proportion of their 
[normal]time communicating
[normal] (in ar
[normal]ticles, 
[normal]at conferences and seminars
[normal]), 
[normal]networking, writing grant proposals, supervising students, managing staff, teaching and
[normal] 
[normal]- 
[normal]increasingly
[normal] 
[normal]-
[normal] 
[normal]performing public outreach activities and working 
[normal]on 
[normal]the commercial exploitation of their findings. 
[normal]Failure to re
[normal]cognise 
[normal]the importance of 
[normal]these overarching activities potentially 
[normal]reinforces 
[normal]gender bias.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“I am
[normal] not good enough for STEM”.
[normal] 
[normal]Women
[normal] come to believe tha
[normal]t they do not hav
[normal]e the talent, skills,
[normal] or motivation r
[normal]equired to advance in a STEM career. They perceive their 
[normal]male 
[normal]peers as better prepared or more motivated than they are.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“
[normal]STEM is not for me”.
[normal]Women
[normal] perceive that STEM career
[normal]s
[normal] do
[normal] 
[normal]not play to their strengths or 
[normal]motivations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“In order to succeed in STEM, one has to sacrific
[normal]e relationships and family”
[normal]Women
[normal] f
[normal]ear that a career in STEM can
[normal]not be reconciled with their (future) domestic life. 
[normal]In contrast, 
[normal]W
[normal]iSTEM members are keen to emphasise 
[normal]that 
[normal]their own experiences
[normal] differ and a
[normal]n academic STEM job 
[normal]often 
[normal]offers greater flexibility than a teaching job
[normal] when it comes to raising 
[normal]a family
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“A STEM career
[normal] requires too much commitment and 
[normal]too many 
[normal]sacrifices for a job with little stability in the early stages and 
[normal]relatively low 
[normal]financial returns.
[normal]”
[normal]The short term nature and 
[normal]need to be 
[normal]high
[normal]ly
[normal] geographical
[normal]ly mobile, particularly during 
[normal]early
[normal]-
[normal]career
[normal], is a major 
[normal]obstacle highlighted by women
[normal], especially when contrasted with the financial rewards and stability other care
[normal]ers with such deman
[normal]d
[normal]s can bring in the long term.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women grad
[normal]uates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Raise 
[normal]general 
[normal]awareness 
[normal]that STEM has historically been a male dominated field and that both women and men need to work towards reducing any continuing in-built bias. This might include awar
[normal]eness
[normal]-
[normal]raising for 
[normal]staff
[normal] at all levels within STEM organisations, as well as targeted training for individuals involved 
[normal]in 
[normal]recruiting and developing staff.
[normal]. It may be appropriate for 
[normal]peer-review processes 
[normal]to be reviewed such that any 
[normal]unconscious bias
[normal] in ass
[normal]essments can be removed from processes 
[normal]and 
[normal]procedures
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Instigate dialog
[normal]ue
[normal] about the STEM culture and diversity and equality issues by holding high visi
[normal]bility lectures followed by
[normal] discussions. An example of good practice comes from the South African Institute of 
[normal]Physics which always includes 
[normal]in its annual conference a plenary lecture on Women in Physics (this year given by a member of our network).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]PhD supervisors, university tuto
[normal]rs and people managing STEM personnel should be trained to 
[normal]take
[normal] into account gender differences
[normal], for instance the Royal Society of Chemistry reports that female chemistry 
[normal]PhDs 
[normal]find the experience to be 
[normal]too isolating
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Funding bodies should 
[normal]require diversi
[normal]ty 
[normal]training 
[normal]on the part of its grant recipients, 
[normal]as well as 
[normal]the 
[normal]training 
[normal]of their own staff managing grant applications.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]When 
[normal]sponsoring
[normal] conferences and other networking events, funding bodies should state that the list of invited speakers is expected to 
[normal]comprise both men and women, and 
[normal]that 
[normal]justification 
[normal]is required 
[normal]when 
[normal]a suitable degree of diversity is not demonstrated.
[normal] Funding bodies should also review the limitations on number of years since PhD for eligibility for some fellowships. This criterion sho
[normal]uld be revised to take career breaks into account. 
[normal]For the latter point
[normal]s
[normal], an example of such good practice comes from the London Mathematical Society. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]PhD co
[normal]urses should include training on
[normal] skills necessary for career advancement such as writing 
[normal]effective 
[normal]grant proposals
[normal] and successful 
[normal]networking
[normal] activities, 
[normal]as well 
[normal]as awareness
[normal]-
[normal]raising with regard to gender 
[normal]bias.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Senior management and leaders of STEM organisations 
[normal]should 
[normal]endeavour to 
[normal]discourage 
[normal]a 
[normal]long-
[normal]working-
[normal]hours culture and promote 
[normal]positive 
[normal]w
[normal]ork/life balance for all staff. 
[normal]F
[normal]lexible working
[normal] arrangements for both men and 
[normal]women should be 
[normal]promoted wherever 
[normal]it 
[normal]can be seen to have no 
[normal]negative
[normal] impact on productivity. In general, job descriptions 
[normal]should be created that can be easily divided into part-time 
[normal]“
[normal]chunks
[normal]”
[normal] that can be shared among several people. 
[normal]Ideally, there should be an aspiration for m
[normal]eetings 
[normal]to 
[normal]be only held during core hours 
[normal]of the day, e.g. 
[normal]between 9:30 and 3pm
[normal], 
[normal]and attendance 
[normal]at 
[normal]mee
[normal]tings (especially if international) via videolink should be routinely enabled whenever possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Senior management and leaders of STEM organisations should endeavour to r
[normal]ecognise that both women and men have responsibilities outside of work and make reaso
[normal]nable allowances 
[normal]equally for both genders
[normal] 
[normal]when this
[normal] does not impact negatively on productivity
[normal] over the medium timescale
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Initiatives should encourage 
[normal]equality of caring duties.
[normal] For example, encourage male employees to take their turn picking their childre
[normal]n up from school and take
[normal] time off when a child is sick
[normal] - t
[normal]oo many schemes, such as flexible and part time working, seem to be aimed at helping women juggle and cope, but still assume that the women do more than their share of the domestic and caring 
[normal]duties. Where possible, allow both men and women to work part time on a temporary basis if there is a problem in the family, wi
[normal]thout losing full-time status. 
[normal]Employers should recognise the increasing need for long term care of elderly relatives will be a s
[normal]ignificant trend over the coming years and 
[normal]recognise the need for 
[normal]gender equality 
[normal]among
[normal] carers
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Quantitative measures of staff and job applicants’ productivity such as number of papers published and h-
[normal]index
[normal] should be replaced 
[normal]with a comprehensive evaluati
[normal]on of the
[normal] person’s contribution to the organi
[normal]s
[normal]ation 
[normal]and the field
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]For example, they should provide 
[normal]acknowledgement and credit
[normal] 
[normal]for tasks such as organisation of group seminars, engagement with visiting school-children, mentoring junior colleagues, taking 
[normal]o
[normal]n 
[normal]placement students, acting as counsellors, 
[normal]to name just a few.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]STEM professions should be 
[normal]more effectively 
[normal]marketed 
[normal]to 
[normal]both genders. 
[normal]Whilst leading edge STEM is clearly driven by tackling 
[normal]very difficult intellectual challenges
[normal], this does not mean that success is founded solely on playing on 
[normal]personal 
[normal]ambition and individual recognition, which some of our members feel to be the case.
[normal] 
[normal]An alternative approach might be to better emphasise STEM’s 
[normal]role in bringing
[normal] change
[normal]s
[normal] to 
[normal]s
[normal]ociety, 
[normal]help
[normal]ing
[normal] solve 
[normal]g
[normal]lobal problems and mak
[normal]ing
[normal] people’s 
[normal]l
[normal]ives better through collaborative working and co-operation
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.11.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]With regard to 
[normal]recruitment
[normal], w
[normal]hen preparing adverts for vacancies, the advert content and language used should appeal to both genders
[normal]. 
[normal]In promo
[normal]tion and internal recruitment procedures, all eligible candidates should be actively encouraged to apply. This 
[normal]sh
[normal]ould 
[normal]help 
[normal]compens
[normal]ate for the tendency of women
[normal] not 
[normal]to 
[normal]put themselves
[normal] 
[normal]forward
[normal] which some of our members have witnessed
[normal]. 
[normal]It is the experience of many women in our network that ambition is not considered a trait that women should display or 
[normal]admit to
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.12.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Peer-reviewed STEM journals should not communicate the manuscript’s author’s names to the reviewers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.13.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to counteract the lack of job stability, the employment structure of 
[normal]many 
[normal]research groups should be modified. At the moment these consist of one group leader with a permanent position and a number of postdoctoral research associates (referred to a
[normal]s postdocs) on fixed term contracts, in addition to PhD students. We propose that the role of senior postdocs should be professionalized by the creation of the permanent role of “researcher” to be associated with groups. This is the structure of research g
[normal]roups in other Countries such as Italy where the retention of women in STEM careers is much higher.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Require 
[normal]that universities
[normal] and other employers of STEM staff 
[normal]choose and 
[normal]set
[normal] organi
[normal]s
[normal]ational 
[normal]targets on 
[normal]numbers of 
[normal]women at the different career stage
[normal]s
[normal] and on equ
[normal]al pay
[normal]. These targets should be made public, together with data on the number of women and pay reviews.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]C
[normal]reate a national mentoring scheme where women at all career stages are paired with a women or man in a more advance
[normal]d
[normal] career
[normal] 
[normal]stage
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]O
[normal]ffer a career advi
[normal]sing service to al
[normal]l PhD students which
[normal] addresses
[normal] the issues of work/life balance
[normal], including real life testimonials.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]O
[normal]ffer starter grants specifically aimed at early career women researchers in STEM, and grants for students and post-docs
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]regardless of gender, 
[normal]returning after a career break.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Our political leaders should engage in a conversation with the 
[normal]n
[normal]ation about gender issues, in particular on the social and economic advantages of sharing work, domestic commitments, and caring responsi
[normal]bilities (for children, the disabled and the elderly) more equally between men and women. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Equalise the rights of women and men with respect to parental leave and make sure that the ratio between pay and childcare costs always makes it more advantageous f
[normal]or both parents to work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Liaise with other governments, 
[normal]the EU and organisations such as the World Economic Forum, which lists the gender issue as one of the key issues to tackle in order to improve the state of the 
[normal]w
[normal]orld.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Encourage 
[normal]the Research Councils
[normal] and other funding bodies to support 
[normal]interdisciplinary research on women in STEM
[normal], the STEM culture,
[normal] 
[normal]and to gather statistics and 
[normal]data especially aimed at quantifying the effects of gender bias in STEM jobs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
